SIMPLE: intention
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intention
<hw>In*ten"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>intention</ets>, L. <ets>intentio</ets>. See <er>Intend</er>, and
cf. <er>Intension</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A stretching or bending of the mind toward an
object; closeness of application; fixedness of attention;
earnestness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Intention</qex> is when the mind, with great earnestness, and
of choice, fixes its view on any idea.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A determination to act in a certain way or to do a
certain thing; purpose; design; <as>as, an <ex>intention</ex> to go to
New York</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hell is paved with good <qex>intentions</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The object toward which the thoughts are directed;
end; aim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In [chronical distempers], the principal <qex>intention</qex> is
to restore the tone of the solid parts.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The state of being strained. See
<er>Intension</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>Any mental apprehension of an
object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>First intention</b></col> <fld>(Logic)</fld>, <cd>a
conception of a thing formed by the first or direct application of the
mind to the individual object; an idea or image; as, <xex>man</xex>,
<xex>stone</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Second intention</b></col>
<fld>(Logic)</fld>, <cd>a conception generalized from first intuition or
apprehension already formed by the mind; an abstract notion; especially,
a classified notion, as <xex>species</xex>, <xex>genus</xex>,
<xex>whiteness</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>To heal by the first
intention</b></col> <fld>(Surg.)</fld>, <cd>to cicatrize, as a wound,
without suppuration.</cd> -- <col><b>To heal by the second
intention</b></col> <fld>(Surg.)</fld>, <cd>to unite after
suppuration.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Design; purpose; object; aim; intent; drift;
purport; meaning. See <er>Design</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intentional</ent>⟦br⟧
